I agree.  Unit test metrics can be a great morale booster (&quot;Look how many
test we wrote this week!&quot;) or a relatively minor and unreliable indicator of
development progress (&quot;0 unit tests so far&quot; tells you something, but really
high numbers don&#39;t necessarily say a lot).  Code coverage is the most
scientific instrument for determining test thoroughness.  Confidence should
be based a lot on code coverage, and a lot on use case requirements being
met and tested.

Scott Stirling
JRun QA
Macromedia

